liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Baja California Peninsula region in Mexico has been pelted with intense rain as tropical storm Hilary makes its way to the US. One person is dead in Mexico amid reports of flash flooding in the peninsula, where some roads were swept away and images on social media showed raging torrents gushing down city streets that have been turned into rivers. In the United States, the storm is already wreaking havoc on flights and sporting events before it's even arrived, and officials are warning residents to remain indoors and keep emergency supplies handy. Though Hilary has been weakening over the last 48 hours as it nears land, it is still set to be the wettest storm ever to hit the US Southwest, according to Zack Taylor, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service (NWS). "This is a dangerous storm," he says. "It's not just the rain totals but the intensity." Reuters is reporting that Hilary is set to dump vast amounts of water on many parts of the US Southwest that are more accustomed to dry conditions. Areas such as Palm Springs, California, which typically gets around 116 millimetres of rain in an entire year, could receive 152mm to 254mm from this one storm. California's Death Valley area, which receives only about 55millimetres of rain per year, could receive 76-101 millimetres of rain from this event.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Tropical storm Hilary makes landfall over Baja California peninsula

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Two male participants in the Ironman Cork competition have died in separate incidents during the 1.9km swimming leg of the 70.3km even t on Sunday in Youghal, Ireland. Reuters says that emergency services pulled the men, aged 40 and 60, from the water. Medical personnel pronounced them dead. "We are deeply saddened to confirm the deaths of two participants in the IRONMAN 70.3 Ireland, Cork 2023 race," organisers posted on Facebook. "During the swim portion of Sunday's race, security personnel provided immediate medical attention upon recognising that the athletes were in need of assistance. "We share our deepest condolences with the families and friends of the athletes and will continue to offer them our support during this difficult time." The event was scheduled to be held on Saturday but was postponed by a day due to the effects of Storm Betty.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Two ironmen die during competition in Ireland

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Canary Islands regional president Fernando Clavijo says police have confirmed that a wildfire raging on the Spanish tourist island of Tenerife was started deliberately. Clavijo said police had opened three lines of investigation but did not say if there had been any arrests. More than 12,000 people have been evacuated from their homes since the fire started on Tuesday. The islands' emergency services said on Sunday that 11,600 hectares of pine forest and scrubland has been burned. The fire, described as the worst in Tenerife in decades, is threatening 11 town areas flanking a steep and craggy mountain area. Access for firefighters is extremely difficult.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Tenerife fires were deliberately lit, says local police
